deck: UK comic from Polystyle, aimed at younger children and using mostly strips based on children's TV shows.
description:
Having changed the focus of their previous "junior" title, TV Comic, to strips aimed at older children, in 1966 Polystyle launched Pippin, named after the lead character in the BBC TV show The Pogles, which was also the basis for the early issue's cover strip. Pippin was squarely aimed at a younger audience, with text usually printed beneath the art panels and strips mostly based on cartoons and puppet TV shows licensed from their respective owners. Pippin's success saw a sister title, Playland, released in 1968, and when Playland was later cancelled in 1975 it was absorbed into Pippin, which temporarily renamed itself Pippin in Playland. After 1044 issues Pippin was eventually cancelled in September 1986, just two days after its twentieth birthday, and it was absorbed into Buttons.

Strips over the years included The Pogles, Andy Pandy, Bagpuss, Bill and Ben (the Flowerpot Men), Camberwick Green, Chigley and Trumpton, The Herbs, Ivor the Engine, Mr Benn, Morph, Sooty and Sweep, and Toytown (with Larry the Lamb).
name: Pippin

description:
At last we have an answer to the question: What do alien kids read?

Who knows how many light-years this beaten-up, weatherworn volume has traveled to land up in the hands of an earthling like you? This rare artifact from another planet is written in an entirely alien language and alphabet, which you may be the first human to decipher.

Whichever galaxy they're from, these interwoven tales prove that some stories are indeed universal — and that others are, well ... weird, bizarre, and clearly not of this world. But no matter how many eyes, legs, or tentacles they have, it's nice to know that aliens too can smile, cry, poop, make friends, be kind or be cruel, fall prey to peer pressure, and sometimes make a total mess of things while trying to do good.
name: A.L.I.E.E.E.N.

deck: British comic published from 1947 by J.B. Allen.
description:
Launched by J.B. Allen in 11th November 1947as Fitness and Sun, with the fifth issue the comic became just Sun. Early issues included keep fit articles, but these were dropped with the title change. Stories were a mix between comic strips and illustrated text pieces. On 24th May 1949 with Sun #41, the comic was taken over by Amalgamated Press, as was Sun's sister comic Comet, and the new editors replaced most of the humour strips with adventure strips. On 20th May 1950, Sun became a weekly title with #57. The final issue was 17th October 1959, when Sun merged with Lion after 558 issues.

Strips included Battler Britton, Swiss Family Robinson, Moko and Boko, Sitting Bull, Penguin Patrol, Sinbad the Sailor, Billy the Kid and Dick Turpin.
name: Sun
